5","abt 1350":"omkring 1350","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1426":"1426","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1444":"1444","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","about 1365":"omkring 1365","from 1347 to 1395":"fra 1347 til 1395","County Tyrone, Irland":"County Tyrone, Irland","Clannaboy, co. antrim, Ireland":"County Antrim, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","County Antrim, Irland":"County Antrim, Irland",", Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Irland","County Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Irland"},"nl":{"1340–1395":"1340–1395","1345–1368":"1345–1368","1350–1426":"1350–1426","1370–1444":"1370–1444","1300–1347":"1300–1347","about 1370":"circa 1370","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","abt 1350":"circa 1350","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1426":"1426","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1444":"1444","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","about 1365":"circa 1365","from 1347 to 1395":"van 1347 to 1395","County Tyrone, Irland":"County Tyrone, Ierland","Clannaboy, co. antrim, Ireland":"County Antrim, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","County Antrim, Irland":"County Antrim, Ierland",", Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ierland","County Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ierland"},"en":{"1340–1395":"1340–1395","1345–1368":"1345–1368","1350–1426":"1350–1426","1370–1444":"1370–1444","1300–1347":"1300–1347","about 1370":"about 1370","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","abt 1350":"about 1350","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1426":"1426","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1444":"1444","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","about 1365":"about 1365","from 1347 to 1395":"from 1347 to 1395","County Tyrone, Irland":"County Tyrone, Ireland","Clannaboy, co. antrim, Ireland":"County Antrim, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","County Antrim, Irland":"County Antrim, Ireland",", Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ireland","County Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ó'Néill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan, Dermot, Liam, Nuala, Bridie, Brigid, Conor, Fintan, John Patrick.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Néill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niall</i>’, an Irish personal name possibly derived from <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’ (see   Neil  ).","History: Bearers of this surname mostly claim descent from Niall Noígíallach (Niall of the Nine Hostages), a legendary king of Ireland who flourished in the 5th century. His descendants, the Ui Neill dynasty, dominated Ireland, on and off, from the 6th to the 10th century. The surname itself can be traced with some confidence to one of these descendants, namely Niall Glúndubh mac Aodha (died 919), High King of Ireland from 911 to 919, with a power base in Tyrone, Ulster."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Neall","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"McNelis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Niallghuis</b> ‘son of <i>Niallghus</i>’, a personal name (intended as complimentary) composed of the personal name <i>Niall</i> (see   O'Neill  ) + <i>gus</i> ‘vigor’. In Irish the combination of [k] and [n] was generally pronounced [kr], Anglicized as the variants   McCreless   and   McCrillis  ."]},{"name":"O'Neal","meanings":["Irish (Longford, Down): variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"O'Niel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Odneal","meanings":["Perhaps an irregular variant of Irish   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Nealon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Nialláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niallán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>Niall</i>, see   O'Neill  ,   Neil  ."]},{"name":"O'Neil","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conn, Donal, Liam, Siobhan, Aileen, Eamon, Michael Patrick, Seamus, Sean Patrick, William Sean.","Irish (Mayo, Tipperary): variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Neil","meanings":["Scottish, English (Lancashire), and Irish (Munster): from the Gaelic personal name <i>Niall</i> (genitive <i>Néill</i>), possibly derived from Irish <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’. In most cases the name probably represents a shortened form of the derived patronymics   McNeill   or the comparable Irish   O'Neill  .","English: variant of   Neal  ."]},{"name":"O'Neel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Lorraine   or variant spelling of   Laurie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lorraine","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin denoting a migrant from the province of <i>Lorraine</i> in eastern France. This derives its name from Latin <i>Lotharingia</i> ‘territory of the people of <i>Lothar</i>’. The latter is a Germanic personal name derived from <i>hlud</i> ‘fame’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. <i>Lorraine</i> began to be used as a girl's name in Scotland in the 19th century, and for a time in the second half of the 20th century enjoyed great popularity, which has since waned."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Muircheartach Ceannfhada MacÉnri, Lord of Clandeboye Ó'Néill was born in 1340, in County Antrim, Ireland as the son of Énri macBrian O'Neill, Prince of Tir-Eoghain. He married Agnes Aine Cumach O'Cathain of the Isles, Limavady about 1365, in County Tyrone, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1395, in Ireland, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1340–1395":"1340–1395","1345–1368":"1345–1368","1350–1426":"1350–1426","1370–1444":"1370–1444","1300–1347":"1300–1347","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1426":"1426","1347":"1347","1368":"1368","1444":"1444",